[49m[38;5;10m+      1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 12.7: Python Implementation Example
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > **Heads up:** This is a deliberately simple, illustrative implementation of the pseudocode walkthrough from Recipe 12.7. It shows one way you could translate a vital-sign trajectory-monitoring pipeline into working Python using boto3 against Amazon Kinesis Data Streams (here represented by an in-memory `MockKinesisStream` that holds vital-sign records as a list), Amazon Kinesis Data Analytics or Amazon Managed Service for Apache Flink (here represented by a synchronous `process_stream` loop that drains the mock stream record by record), Amazon DynamoDB (here represented by `MockTable` instances for the patient-state table and the alert table), Amazon S3 (here represented by a `MockS3` dict for the historical-vitals warm store and the suppressed-alert log), Amazon SageMaker (here represented by pure-Python `EarlyWarningScorer`, `ArtifactDetector`, and `TrajectorySlopeDetector` classes that stand in for real model endpoints), AWS Lambda (here represented by plain Python functions wired to the stream loop), Amazon EventBridge (here represented by a `MockEventBus`), Amazon CloudWatch (here represented by a `MockCloudWatch`), and Amazon SNS (here represented by a `MockSnsTopic` that prints what would have paged the rapid response team). The demo generates a synthetic two-hour stream of vital signs for four patients with realistic deterioration patterns (a sepsis-like trajectory with rising heart rate and respiratory rate plus falling blood pressure, a COPD exacerbation with falling oxygen saturation, a stable post-op recovery, and a pulse-oximeter sensor dropout that should be filtered as artifact and not paged) so you can see the artifact filtering, the per-patient baseline, the early warning score composition, the trajectory slope detection, and the alert deduplication logic work end-to-end without provisioning anything. It is not production-ready. There is no real Kinesis stream, no real Flink application, no real SageMaker endpoint, no real DynamoDB table, no real EventBridge bus, no real CloudWatch alarms, no real SNS topic, no real device gateway integration, no per-Lambda IAM least privilege, no KMS customer-managed keys, no VPC endpoints, no acuity-tier-aware alert routing, no clinician-feedback capture, no medication-aware suppression, no continuous device-quality monitoring, and no real-time waveform analysis. Think of it as the sketchpad version: useful for understanding the shape of a deterioration-monitoring pipeline that respects the artifact-first discipline, the patient-as-their-own-control discipline, the multi-parameter-composite-score discipline, the slope-and-magnitude-and-persistence triple-gate discipline, and the alert-fatigue-is-the-failure-mode discipline this recipe demands. It is not something you would point at a real telemetry floor on Monday morning. Consider it a starting point, not a destination.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m >
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > The code maps to the five pseudocode steps from the main recipe: ingest the vital-sign record from the device gateway, validate that every required field is present, normalize the units, and tag the patient acuity tier (Step 1); apply the artifact filter that catches sensor dropouts, motion artifact, and physiologically impossible values before they pollute the trajectory (Step 2); update the per-patient state object with the cleaned reading and recompute the rolling baseline using the most recent stable window (Step 3); compute the composite early warning score (an illustrative NEWS2-shaped composite) and run the per-parameter trajectory slope detector to catch slow deterioration before any single value crosses a threshold (Step 4); apply the alert-suppression rules that gate on persistence, deduplication, escalation tier, and the patient's existing alert state, then write surfaced alerts to the alert table, write suppressed alerts to S3 for tuning, page the appropriate response tier via SNS, and emit lifecycle events to EventBridge (Step 5). The synthetic patients, the synthetic acuity tiers, the synthetic deterioration trajectories, and the synthetic NEWS2-shaped scoring in the demo are fictional; nothing in this file should be interpreted as real clinical data from any real institution or as a clinically validated early warning score.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Setup
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m You will need the AWS SDK for Python:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```bash
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m pip install boto3
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The demo runs against the Python standard library plus boto3; no other packages are imported. Production deployments swap the demo's pure-Python detectors for real statistical libraries ([scipy](https://docs.scipy.org/doc/scipy/) for the slope and outlier helpers, [statsmodels](https://www.statsmodels.org/stable/) for the autoregressive baseline that handles the irregular sampling, [numpy](https://numpy.org/) for the windowed array math) and replace the synchronous `process_stream` loop with a real Apache Flink application running on Amazon Managed Service for Apache Flink, with the per-record stateful logic implemented as Flink keyed-stream operators rather than Python dict updates. The Gap to Production section spells out the substitutions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m In production you would also configure an Amazon Kinesis Data Stream for the vital-sign telemetry feed (one shard per a few thousand monitored patients, with the patient identifier as the partition key so all of a patient's records land on the same shard), an Amazon S3 bucket for the historical-vitals warm store, the suppressed-alert log, the device-quality-metric prefix, and the model-artifact prefix (one prefix per concern, all SSE-KMS encrypted with a customer-managed key), an Amazon Managed Service for Apache Flink application that runs the per-patient stateful logic (artifact filter, baseline update, score composition, slope detection, alert suppression) at the per-record cadence the device gateway emits, an Amazon SageMaker inference endpoint hosting any model components that benefit from being managed model artifacts (a learned artifact classifier, a per-acuity-tier slope-detector ensemble, an attention-based deterioration model layered on top of the rule-based composite), an Amazon DynamoDB table for the per-patient state object keyed by `patient_id` (current vitals, rolling baseline, current alert state, last-paged timestamp), an Amazon DynamoDB table for the surfaced-alert ledger keyed by `patient_id` with a sort key combining `alert_type` and `generated_at`, an Amazon EventBridge bus for the pipeline-lifecycle events (record processed, artifact filtered, alert surfaced, alert suppressed, alert acknowledged), an Amazon SNS topic for the rapid-response team page (with separate topics or message attributes for the acuity tiers so the rapid response team and the bedside RN do not get the same page), Amazon CloudWatch dashboards and alarms for pipeline failures, surfaced-alert volume per unit, alert-acknowledgment latency, device-quality drift, and end-to-end record latency, and a thin integration layer that exposes acknowledged alerts to the EHR's flowsheet and the bedside monitor for closed-loop accountability. The demo replaces all of these with a single in-process Python file so the focus stays on the artifact filtering, the baseline math, the score composition, the slope detection, and the alert-suppression decision rather than on the platform plumbing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Your environment needs credentials configured (via environment variables, an instance profile, or `~/.aws/credentials`). The IAM role or user needs:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `kinesis:PutRecord`, `kinesis:PutRecords`, `kinesis:GetShardIterator`, `kinesis:GetRecords`, and `kinesis:DescribeStream` on the vital-sign telemetry stream, scoped to the specific stream ARN
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `s3:GetObject` and `s3:PutObject` on the historical-vitals warm-store prefix, the suppressed-alert prefix, the device-quality-metric prefix, and the model-artifact prefix
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `dynamodb:GetItem`, `dynamodb:PutItem`, `dynamodb:UpdateItem`, and `dynamodb:Query` on the `patient-vital-state` table and the `patient-vital-alerts` table, scoped to the specific table ARNs
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `sagemaker:InvokeEndpoint` on the artifact-classifier endpoint and any per-acuity-tier slope detectors
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `events:PutEvents` on the vital-sign-events bus for emitting pipeline-lifecycle events
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `sns:Publish` on the rapid-response-pager topic and the bedside-RN-pager topic
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `cloudwatch:PutMetricData` for the operational metrics (per-unit alert volume, artifact-filter rate, end-to-end record latency, model inference latency, suppression-by-reason counts)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `kms:Decrypt` and `kms:GenerateDataKey` on the customer-managed keys protecting the Kinesis stream, the S3 prefixes, the DynamoDB tables, the SageMaker model artifacts, and the SNS topics
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Scope each Lambda's IAM role to the specific resource ARNs it touches. The tutorial-level permissions above are fine for learning and will fail any serious IAM review. The Flink application reads from the Kinesis stream, writes to DynamoDB and S3, and publishes to SNS and EventBridge, but never touches the model-artifact bucket or any other patient's record outside its keyed-stream partition. Avoid wildcard actions and resources in production.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few things worth knowing upfront:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Vital signs are PHI in their entirety.** Patient identifier, parameter name, value, timestamp, monitor location. Every storage and compute service that touches this pipeline must be on the [HIPAA eligible services](https://aws.amazon.com/compliance/hipaa-eligible-services-reference/) list, every storage layer must be encrypted with customer-managed KMS keys, every network hop must be inside the institutional VPC with no public path, and CloudTrail must log every data-plane API call. The aggregated alert records still carry the patient identifier; they remain PHI even after the underlying values are summarized into a score.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Artifact filtering is not optional.** Pulse oximeters fall off, ECG leads detach, blood-pressure cuffs deflate mid-cycle, and the bedside monitor cheerfully streams the resulting garbage values at the same frequency as a real reading. A pipeline that lets a "heart rate of 0" through to the early warning score will page rapid response on a sensor dropout, the unit will lose trust within a week, and the project is dead. The artifact filter is the first stage and the highest-value engineering investment in the entire pipeline.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Patient-specific baselines beat population thresholds.** A resting heart rate of 102 is an alert-worthy tachycardia in most patients and is the calibrated normal for a patient on a beta blocker holiday with chronic atrial fibrillation. The composite score uses population norms because it has to be standardized for clinical use, but the trajectory detector compares each parameter to that patient's own rolling baseline. Both layers exist; either one alone misses cases.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Slope matters more than threshold crossings.** The patient whose respiratory rate has crept from 16 to 22 over four hours is more concerning than the patient whose respiratory rate has been a stable 24 for three days. The slope detector catches the former; a threshold-only system catches the latter and misses the former. The composite score is the safety net for the latter; the trajectory detector is the early-warning instrument for the former.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Persistence gates are how you survive alert fatigue.** A single high reading is rarely worth a page. A reading that has been high for ten of the last fifteen samples is. The persistence gate is the cheapest and most effective alert-suppression mechanism in the pipeline; production pipelines have several of them tuned per parameter and per acuity tier.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Deduplication is non-negotiable.** A patient who has already triggered a rapid-response page at 14:32 should not generate a second page at 14:33 because their heart rate is still elevated. The alert state on the patient-state table tracks "this patient is in active alert" and suppresses repeat pages until the alert is acknowledged or the patient returns to baseline. Without this, a single deterioration produces dozens of pages and the unit stops paying attention to any of them.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **DynamoDB rejects Python `float`.** Every score, slope, baseline value, deviation, threshold, and confidence value passes through `Decimal` on its way in and on its way out. The `_to_decimal` helper handles it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **The example collapses many Lambdas, Flink operators, and SageMaker endpoints into a single Python file.** In production the artifact filter, the baseline updater, the score composer, the slope detector, the alert-suppression evaluator, the alert-pager, and the suppressed-alert logger are separate units of work with their own IAM roles, error handling, retries, and DLQs. Comments call out where the boundaries should fall.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Configuration and Constants
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Everything that is configuration rather than logic lives here. Resource names, the per-parameter NEWS2-shaped score table, the per-parameter physiological bounds, the per-parameter slope thresholds, the per-acuity-tier alert routing, the persistence-gate windows, and the synthetic-data parameters are what you would change between environments.
