[49m[38;5;10m+    1794[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1795[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1796[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Gap to Production
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1797[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1798[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The demo is intentionally a sketch. Here is the distance between this code and something you would deploy.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1799[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1800[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Real Apache Flink, not a Python loop.** The `process_stream` loop iterates the mock stream synchronously. Production runs an [Amazon Managed Service for Apache Flink](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/managed-flink/latest/java/what-is.html) application with the patient identifier as the keyed-stream key. Each per-patient operator holds the state in RocksDB-backed keyed state, persists checkpoints to S3 every minute, and recovers automatically from operator failure. The artifact filter, the baseline updater, the score composer, the slope detector, and the alert evaluator are each Flink operators (or stages of a `KeyedProcessFunction`); the per-record latency stays in the tens of milliseconds at thousands of records per second. The Python loop here demonstrates the stateful logic but not the streaming execution model that production needs.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1801[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1802[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Real Kinesis stream, not MockKinesisStream.** Replace `MockKinesisStream` with `boto3.client('kinesis')` calls. Production uses one Kinesis Data Stream for the vital-sign telemetry feed, partitioned by patient identifier so all of a patient's records land on the same shard and the keyed-stream operators see a consistent state. Shard count scales with the number of monitored patients (a rule of thumb: one shard per ~3,000 monitored patients, with a one-second sample period per parameter and five parameters per patient). Enable [Enhanced Fan-Out](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/streams/latest/dev/introduction-to-enhanced-consumers.html) on the Flink application's consumer for sub-200ms end-to-end latency. Use Kinesis server-side encryption with a customer-managed KMS key.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1803[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1804[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Real DynamoDB, not MockTable.** Replace `MockTable` with `boto3.resource('dynamodb').Table(name)`. The patient-state table needs a partition key (`patient_id`, type S), encryption-at-rest with a customer-managed KMS key, point-in-time recovery enabled, and on-demand billing for the unpredictable load that comes with shift change. The alert-ledger table needs the same plus a sort key (`tier_generated_at`, type S) so the EHR's flowsheet integration can query the patient's alert history by date range. Both tables benefit from [DynamoDB Streams](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/amazondynamodb/latest/developerguide/Streams.html) so the EHR integration layer can react to acknowledgments. Handle the `BatchWriteItem` `UnprocessedItems` response with exponential backoff; `MockTable` ignores this case but DynamoDB returns unprocessed items under throttling.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1805[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1806[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Real SNS, not MockSnsTopic.** Replace `MockSnsTopic` with `boto3.client('sns').publish(...)`. Production uses two topics (one per acuity tier) with [message-attribute filtering](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/sns/latest/dg/sns-subscription-filter-policies.html) so subscribers can pick the alerts they want. The rapid-response topic subscribes the rapid response team's secure messaging app and a backup pager group; the bedside-RN topic subscribes the unit's pager group and the unit clerk's dashboard. Both topics need server-side encryption with a customer-managed KMS key because the message payload contains PHI. Use [SNS message archiving](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/sns/latest/dg/message-archiving-and-replay.html) so the audit trail captures every page that went out, not just the ones that reached a subscriber.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1807[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1808[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Real S3, not MockS3.** Replace `MockS3` with `boto3.client('s3')` calls. Production has separate prefixes for the historical-vitals warm store (queried for the rolling baseline if Flink state is lost), the suppressed-alert log, the device-quality metrics, the dead-letter records, and the model artifacts, all encrypted with the same customer-managed KMS key. Object-level retention policies match the institutional retention floor (typically seven years for clinical operational records). Use [S3 Object Lock](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/userguide/object-lock.html) on the suppressed-alert prefix and the alert-ledger checkpoint so the audit log cannot be tampered with.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1809[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1810[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Real SageMaker endpoints for the artifact classifier and the deterioration model.** The `ArtifactDetector` and `TrajectorySlopeDetector` in this file are pedagogical. Production hosts a learned artifact classifier (a small gradient-boosted model trained on labeled artifact and clean samples, with features including the device-quality metadata, the recent residuals, the variance of the last few samples, and the time since the last clean reading) on a SageMaker endpoint, fronted by a Lambda that the Flink operator invokes for the residual-check stage of the layered filter. A separate endpoint hosts a learned deterioration model (a sequence model that takes the last hour of multi-parameter samples and returns a calibrated deterioration probability) that augments the rule-based composite. Both endpoints run in a private VPC with VPC endpoints to KMS and CloudWatch Logs.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1811[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1812[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Real EventBridge bus and CloudWatch alarms.** The `MockEventBus` and `MockCloudWatch` accumulate events and metrics in process. Production uses real `boto3.client('events').put_events(...)` and `boto3.client('cloudwatch').put_metric_data(...)`, plus CloudWatch alarms on per-unit alert volume (alarm if pages per RN per shift exceeds tolerance, which is the leading indicator of alert fatigue creeping in), end-to-end record latency (alarm if p95 exceeds two seconds), DynamoDB write throttling, SageMaker endpoint 5xx rate, and artifact-filter rate (alarm if a single device's artifact rate spikes, which usually indicates a misplaced or failing sensor). The alarms feed an SNS topic that pages the on-call ML engineer.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1813[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1814[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Device-gateway integration is messy.** The demo synthesizes records directly into the stream. Production reads from the bedside monitor network, which is one of: an HL7 v2 ORU-R01 stream over MLLP, an [IHE PCD-01](https://wiki.ihe.net/index.php/Patient_Care_Device) bedside-device profile feed, a vendor-specific MQTT stream from a connected-medical-device gateway (Capsule, Bernoulli, Connexall), or a direct API integration with the bedside monitor vendor (Philips IntelliVue, GE CARESCAPE, Mindray BeneVision). Each of these has its own transport, its own message schema, its own quality-of-service guarantees, and its own gotchas. The device-gateway service that translates from the vendor protocol to the Kinesis record schema is typically a long-running ECS or Fargate service that handles thousands of devices simultaneously, with per-device monitoring and reconnection logic. Plan for the device-gateway to be the single biggest source of operational pain in the project for the first six months.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1815[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1816[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Acuity-tier-aware calibration.** The demo uses a single set of thresholds for all patients on all units. Production calibrates per-unit (med-surg, telemetry, step-down, ICU) because the baselines and the slope tolerances are wildly different across acuity tiers (an ICU patient's HR climbing from 90 to 110 over an hour is not the alert that the same trajectory would be on a med-surg floor; the ICU patient's nurse is already in the room). The catalog grows a third dimension (parameter, acuity_tier, threshold) and the score-band tables become per-tier. Operationally, this means the rules library doubles or triples in size and the rule-tuning cycle becomes an explicit per-unit calibration ritual.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1817[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1818[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Medication-aware suppression.** A patient who just received a dose of nebulized albuterol will have an elevated heart rate for thirty minutes; that is expected, not concerning. A patient on a beta blocker holiday has a different chronic baseline than the same patient last week. The demo has no concept of medication context. Production integrates the medication administration record (MAR) feed and applies medication-aware suppression: a recent albuterol dose suppresses HR-trajectory alarms for thirty minutes; a recent narcotic dose lowers the bar for SpO2 trajectory alarms; a recent vasopressor titration changes the SBP baseline calibration. This is the single most important refinement after the basic pipeline works.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1819[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1820[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Acknowledgment loop and feedback capture.** Every page should have a feedback path: was this useful, was the patient already known to be deteriorating, did the team take action. The demo's alert ledger has an `acknowledged` field but no closed loop. Production captures the clinician's acknowledgment via the secure messaging app's read receipt, writes an acknowledgment event to the alert ledger, and surfaces unacknowledged alerts to the charge nurse after a configurable timeout. The acknowledgments feed a feedback table that drives weekly rule-tuning meetings. Without this, the system stays calibrated to its launch-day rules forever and the unit's tolerance for alerts erodes month over month.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1821[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1822[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Joint-parameter reasoning.** Some deteriorations matter much more in combination than in isolation. A rising heart rate plus a rising respiratory rate plus a falling SBP is sepsis until proven otherwise; any one of those alone might be a false alarm. The demo's composite score sums independent points and does not weight combinations. Production layers a learned model on top of the rule-based composite to catch the combinations the rules miss; this is where Recipe 3.7 (patient deterioration early warning) and Recipe 7.x (predictive analytics) start to overlap with this recipe.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1823[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1824[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Triage and escalation pathways.** A surfaced alert is just the start. Production has explicit escalation pathways: bedside-RN gets the watch-tier alert; if not acknowledged in 5 minutes, the charge RN gets it; if not acknowledged in 10 minutes, the rapid response team gets it regardless of the original tier. The escalation pathways are unit-specific and shift-specific (night shift has different staffing than day shift), and they integrate with the institution's existing rapid response activation protocol. Without the escalation logic, an unacknowledged page is an unactioned page.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1825[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1826[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Network resilience.** Bedside monitors are on the institutional medical-device VLAN, which is intentionally segmented from the rest of the network. The device gateway has to handle network partitions gracefully (buffer to local disk, replay when connectivity returns), the Flink application has to handle Kinesis-side backpressure when the device gateway catches up, and the SNS pager has to handle subscriber failures (a paged clinician whose phone is dead must result in escalation, not a silent drop). The demo has no network at all; production has to design for partial failures at every hop.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1827[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1828[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **HIPAA controls end-to-end.** The Kinesis stream uses encryption with a customer-managed KMS key; the S3 prefixes use SSE-KMS with the same key family; the DynamoDB tables use encryption-at-rest with a customer-managed key; the SNS topics use server-side encryption; the SageMaker endpoints run in a VPC with VPC endpoints to S3, KMS, and CloudWatch Logs; CloudTrail logs all Kinesis, S3, DynamoDB, SNS, EventBridge, and SageMaker API calls; CloudWatch log groups are KMS-encrypted; IAM roles are scoped to specific resource ARNs; an AWS BAA is in place. The demo touches none of this; production cannot ship without all of it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1829[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1830[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Audit trail.** Each pipeline run is identified by a `run_id`, all surfaced alerts carry that run_id and the model + rule + score-table versions, the DynamoDB writes overwrite cleanly by the `(patient_id, tier_generated_at)` key, and the suppressed-alert S3 writes use deterministic prefixes so a rerun produces the same output. An immutable audit log captures which rule version produced which page on which night, written through Kinesis Data Firehose into an Object-Lock S3 bucket sized to the institutional retention floor.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1831[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1832[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Testing.** Unit tests cover the ingestion validator (a missing field is rejected, a non-numeric value is rejected, an unknown parameter is rejected), the unit-conversion helper (Fahrenheit to Celsius is correct, an unsupported conversion returns None), the artifact filter (a value below physio_min is hard-rejected, a non-OK device-quality tag rejects the value, a 6-MAD residual is flagged suspicious), the baseline calculation (insufficient history returns the right status, a known-input series produces the expected interquartile mean), the score composer (the NEWS2-shaped band edges produce the expected points, the tier-promotion logic from slope alarms works), the slope detector (a flat input produces a near-zero slope, a known-slope input produces the expected per-hour slope, the persistence calculation matches the expected window), the alert-evaluator (a borderline-significant alert is suppressed when below the persistence window, surfaced when above; a refractory-window block prevents duplicate pages; a higher tier bypasses a lower tier's refractory). Integration tests run the full pipeline against the synthetic stream and assert the surfaced and suppressed counts against expected values. End-to-end tests stand up real Kinesis, DynamoDB, SNS, and EventBridge resources in a sandbox account and run the Flink application.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1833[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1834[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Structured logging.** Replace the demo's `print` calls with `logger.info(..., extra={...})` calls that emit JSON-formatted structured logs to CloudWatch Logs. Log structural metadata only (run_id, patient_id_hash, parameter, tier_label, surface_decision, runtime_ms), never raw values, never timestamps tied to identifiable rooms, never the per-acuity-tier thresholds that include the institution's calibration choices.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1835[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1836[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Regulatory framing.** Vital-sign trajectory monitoring that triggers actionable rapid-response calls sits squarely in the FDA software-as-a-medical-device (SaMD) conversation. A pipeline that is purely advisory (surfaces a trend on the bedside monitor for the RN to review) is largely exempt from FDA premarket review under the 21st Century Cures Act if it meets specific transparency and explainability requirements (the explanation text on the surfaced payload is doing real work here). A pipeline that automatically activates the rapid response team is much closer to active clinical decision support and may require [510(k) clearance](https://www.fda.gov/medical-devices/premarket-submissions-selecting-and-preparing-correct-submission/premarket-notification-510k) depending on how the activation is framed. Working with regulatory counsel on the framing of the surfaced output is non-negotiable for any deployment that goes beyond a research pilot.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1837[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1838[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The shape of the gap.** The trajectory math in this file is a sketch but it is fundamentally correct. The plumbing around it (device-gateway integration, streaming execution model, joint-parameter reasoning, medication-aware suppression, acuity-tier-aware calibration, escalation pathways, acknowledgment capture, security, regulatory framing) is what takes the bulk of the engineering work. Plan for the plumbing to be 85% of the project; the trajectory detection itself routinely surprises teams by being the easier part.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1839[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1840[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1841[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1842[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Related Resources
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1843[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1844[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - TODO: Link to [Recipe 12.7: Vital Sign Trajectory Monitoring](chapter12.07-vital-sign-trajectory-monitoring) once the main recipe is drafted. The main recipe contains the full architectural walkthrough this Python companion implements.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1845[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - [Recipe 3.7: Patient Deterioration Early Warning](chapter03.07-patient-deterioration-early-warning): The recipe that overlaps most with this one. The deterioration recipe focuses on the learned-model side; this recipe focuses on the rule-based composite plus per-patient trajectory layer.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1846[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - [Recipe 12.4: Lab Result Trend Analysis](chapter12.04-lab-result-trend-analysis): The chronic-trend cousin of this real-time pipeline. The same baseline, persistence, and clinical-relevance discipline applies; the cadence is the major difference.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1847[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - [Amazon Kinesis Data Streams Documentation](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/streams/latest/dev/introduction.html): The streaming platform that backs the per-record telemetry feed.
